Following the crucial Ancient_Greece victory at the naval Battle of Battle_of_Salamis in September 480 Common_Era, Xerxes_I’ planned invasion of Ancient_Greece met a serious setback but his massive army was still intact, and if the Ancient_Greece were to survive as independent city-states they would have to fight and win on land; the battlefield would be near the small town of Battle_of_Plataea in Boeotia in 479 Common_Era. The Ancient_Greece Hoplite, as at Battle_of_Marathon eleven years before, once again proved more than a match for the Achaemenid_Empire invader, and a victory was won which would not only guarantee freedom from foreign rule, but also permit an astonishingly rich period of artistic and cultural HMS_Endeavour which would lay the cultural foundations of all future Western civilizations. 

By the first years of the 5th century Common_Era, Achaemenid_Empire, under the rule of Darius_I (r. 522-486 Common_Era), was already expanding into mainland Europe and had subjugated Thrace and Republic_of_Macedonia. The next objective was to quell once and for all the collection of potentially troublesome rebel states on the western border of the Roman_Empire. In 490 Common_Era Ancient_Greece forces led by History_of_Athens met the Achaemenid_Empire in Battle at Battle_of_Marathon and defeated the invaders. The Battle would take on mythical status amongst the Ancient_Greece, but in reality it was merely the opening Overture of a long war with several other battles making up the principal acts. In 486 Common_Era Xerxes_I became king, and he invaded first the Cyclades and then the Ancient_Greece mainland after victory against a token Ancient_Greece force at Battle_of_Thermopylae in August 480 Common_Era. At the same time as Battle_of_Thermopylae, an indecisive Naval_warfare took place at Artemisium, where the Ancient_Greece held off the superior numbers of the Achaemenid_Empire fleet but were obliged to regroup at Battle_of_Salamis. In September 490 Common_Era, with the brilliant general Themistocles dictating strategy, the allied Ancient_Greece fleet drew the Achaemenid_Empire into the narrow confines of the straits between Battle_of_Salamis and the mainland and won a resounding victory.

Following the defeat of his armada and the close of the campaign season, Xerxes_I returned home to his palace at John_Philip_Sousa and left the Child_prodigy general Mardonius in charge of the invasion. The Achaemenid_Empire position was still strong despite the defeat at sea - they still controlled much of Ancient_Greece and their huge land army was intact. Xerxes_I may well have hoped that the fragile Ancient_Greece alliance between such age-old rivals as History_of_Athens and Sparta would break if appropriate diplomatic overtures were made, but after a series of political negotiations, it became clear that the Achaemenid_Empire would not gain victory through diplomacy and only war would settle the issue.

The vast Persian Roman_Empire stretched from the Danube to Ptolemaic_Kingdom and from Ionia to Bactria, and Xerxes_I was able to draw on a huge Military_reserve of resources to amass his huge invasion force. Overall command was now taken by Mardonius, the son-in-law and nephew of Darius_I and cousin of Xerxes_I. By his side was Artabazos_I_of_Phrygia (a cousin of Darius_I) who led the Parthia and Khwarezmian_language contingents. 

Our numbers for the soldiers involved in the Battle come principally from Herodotus who wrote an account of Battle_of_Plataea in his Herodotus; however, the absolute accuracy of Herodotus’ estimates are disputed amongst scholars. According to Herodotus, the Achaemenid_Empire fielded 350,000 troops against the Ancient_Greece forces of 108,200. The figures for the Achaemenid_Empire may have been exaggerated in order to make the Achaemenid_Empire into a more Formidable-class_frigate opponent, and perhaps in reality they fielded a very similar number of combatants to the Ancient_Greece. However, even with a more conservative estimate, the Battle involved some 200,000 armed men, the largest such Battle Ancient_Greece had seen and a figure comparable with the battles of Battle_of_Waterloo and Battle_of_Gettysburg.

