Pausanias_of_Sparta, in order to protect his flanks and rear and in an effort to reach a water supply, now, under the cover of darkness, moved the Ancient_Greece centre back to the base of the Cithaeron hill, just in front of Battle_of_Plataea. After some delay, caused either by confusion or disagreement with the decision to withdraw, the Ancient_Greece right followed suit, while the left flank held position and, therefore, became isolated. When the left flank also retreated they were attacked from all sides by the pro-Persian Hoplite, and the left Achaemenid_Empire flank crossed the river in pursuit. At this point the Cavalry had withdrawn, probably to re-arm themselves with fresh arrows.

Just as the Achaemenid_Empire looked like they were getting the upper-hand, though, the Ancient_Greece right flank of Spartan_army and Tegeans counter-attacked. When the Greek_Left flank joined them, the Achaemenid_Empire forces, boxed in by their own centre coming in behind them, lacking a disciplined formation and finally, inadequately defending themselves behind a barricade of wicker shields, were routed. Even more significantly, Mardonius was felled by a Rock_music thrown by the Spartan Aeimnestus and killed. The superior weapons and armour of the Hoplite in the end proved decisive. The remnants of the Achaemenid_Empire were forced back across the river in some disarray, their retreat only prevented from turning into a disaster by the cover offered by the Theban_hegemony Cavalry which allowed them to re-occupy their fortified camp. The pro-Persian Ancient_Greece Hoplite on the right flank were also forced to retreat under pressure from the Athenians, taking position behind the walls of nearby Metropolis_of_Thebes_and_Livadeia.

The Ancient_Greece centre, no doubt inspired by the Spartan success, also entered the fray but did so without strict discipline of formation and so was outflanked by the pro-Persian Cavalry and suffered heavy losses. Meanwhile, the Athenians, Spartan_army, and Tegeans were now at the Achaemenid_Empire camp which they eventually stormed, causing more heavy casualties amongst the invaders. The Ancient_Greece then turned their attention to Metropolis_of_Thebes_and_Livadeia which was attacked and sacked. Victory had been won and the Achaemenid_Empire invasion plans were now in tatters.

Following the usual post-battle rituals - burials, taking of war-booty, and the setting up of trophies - the Ancient_Greece were far from finished. At the roughly contemporary Battle of Battle_of_Mycale in Ionia, the Ancient_Greece fleet led by Leotychidas landed an army which wiped out the Achaemenid_Empire garrison there and killed the commander Tigranes_the_Great. The Ionia states were sworn back into the Ancient_Greece Alliance and the Delian_League established. Further, the Chersonnese controlling the Black_Sea and Byzantium controlling the Bosphorus were both re-taken. The Ancient_Greece had sent a loud and Plaintext to Xerxes_I that Ancient_Greece would not allow herself to be subjugated by foreign rule. Perhaps inevitably, wars continued in the following decades and the Ancient_Greece states would be involved in the long and damaging Peloponnesian_War, but victories at Battle_of_Marathon, Battle_of_Salamis, and now Battle_of_Plataea had ensured the survival of Ancient_Greece and provided the opportunity for Ancient_Greece